						<div class=3D"content_section">
		<p>
			*Use the entry fields above to enter the <i>final dimensions</i> that yo=
u want your pottery piece to be=20
			after it is bisqued and glaze fired.=20
			Based on your clay's shrink rate, the online clay shrinkage ruler will t=
hen reverse calculate the=20
			approximate size that your piece should be in the greenware state (ie. b=
efore it dries and is kiln fired).
		</p>
		<p>
			Keep in mind that as with any shrinkage ruler,=20
			these calculations are approximations and the final piece may be slightl=
y larger or smaller. Several factors,=20
			including firing time and temperature, can vary slightly per kiln, which=
 can impact the actual shrinkage.
		</p>
	=09
		<h2>Determining Clay Shrinkage</h2>
		<p>
			The clay manufacturer or distributor should have=20
			specs, including clay shrinkage at the various firing temperatures. If y=
ou work in a studio,=20
			they will likely have this information, and, if you buy your own clay, c=
heck with the ceramics store.=20
		</p>
		<p>
			You can also run your own test on how much your clay shrinks, using=20
			our <a href=3D"https://photopottery.com/clay-shrink-test-calculator.php"=
>Clay Shrink Test Calculator</a>.
		</p>
	=09
		<h2>Make Bigger Pots, Replacement Lids</h2>
		<p>
			If you've ever been surpised by the diminished size of your piece when i=
t comes out of=20
			the glaze kiln, this reverse clay shrink calculator=20
			can help you make pottery that's very close to the size you want.=20
					</p>
		<p>=09
						Another advantage of this shrink calculator is for making replacement=
 lids. For example, if=20
			your teapot lid breaks, you can reverse calculate the lid's size based o=
n the finished=20
			teapot's lid area.=20
		</p>
	</div>
